{"id": 68973, "date": "1988-07-01T09:00:33", "date_gmt": "1988-07-01T16:00:33", "guid": {"rendered": "https://estreetshuffle.com/?p=68973"}, "modified": "2026-05-11T21:13:23", "modified_gmt": "2026-05-12T04:13:23", "slug": "preface-5", "status": "publish", "type": "post", "link": "https://estreetshuffle.com/index.php/1988/07/01/preface-5/", "title": {"rendered": "Preface"}, "content": {"rendered": "<p>This is the inevitable companion volume I promised in <em>Cover Me Volume Three: With a Little Help From My Friends.\u00a0</em></p>\n<p>It collects the remainder of the\u00a0<em>Meeting Across the River\u00a0</em>posts featuring Bruce Springsteen teaming up with other artists on their own songs, including four brand-new entries never published on the blog: &#8220;Dustland,&#8221; &#8220;Did You Say Such a Thing,&#8221; &#8220;Barbara Ann,&#8221; and &#8220;Rose Tattoo.&#8221;</p>\n<p>I&#8217;ve also included my marathon <em>American Babylon</em>\u00a0 interview with Joe Grushecky from October 2020 as sort of a &#8220;bonus track.&#8221; It was my second long-form interview with Joe, and it laced my long-time admiration of him as artist with genuine affection for him as a conversationalist.</p>\n<p>We&#8217;d go on to have many more back-and-forths over the following years whenever I would sit down to write a <em>Meeting Across the River</em> essay on one of his songs, or a\u00a0<em>Roll of the Dice</em> entry for one of his co-authored songs with Bruce.</p>\n<p>One of the pleasures of writing the blog over the years was learning more about other artists and gaining greater appreciation for their work. As I flip through these pages, I see many songs I wasn&#8217;t familiar with before I started the Shuffle, and lots of new-to-me nuggets for ones that I thought I knew.</p>\n<p>I hope you discover some new treats as you flip through this volume, too.</p>\n<p>\u00a9 May 11, 2026</p>\n", "protected": false}, "excerpt": {"rendered": "<p>This is the inevitable companion volum